The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Hindalco to offer 1:4 rights

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Birla: New horizon

 Mumbai, Sept. 20: Non-ferrous metals manufacturer Hindalco Industries will raise up to Rs 2,500 crore through a rights issue in the ratio of one equity share for every four held. 

 The proceeds of the issue will be utilised for part-financing various projects under implementation. Hindalco has planned expansion projects with a total investment outlay of around Rs 12,000 crore.

 The decision to make a rights issue was taken at a board meeting of Hindalco held today. 

 However, the company said the issue price (per share) would be decided at a later stage, based on the amount to be raised and the share ratio, analysts expect it to be pegged at Rs 108 per share. This is a discount of nearly 33 per cent to the scrips closing price of Rs 160.80 at the BSE today.

 It has been decided that subscribers to the issue will have to pay 25 per cent of the issue price as application money, another 25 per cent between 9 and 12 months from the date of allotment of shares and the balance 50 per cent between 18 and 24 months.

 The brownfield expansions include increasing the capacities of its alumina manufacturing facilities at Muri in Jharkhand to 4.50 lakh tonnes from 1.10 lakh tonnes and at Belgaum in Karnataka to 6.50 lakh tonnes from 3.50 lakh tonnes. The company is also expanding the aluminium facilities at Hirakud in Orissa to 1.46 lakh tonnes from 65,000 tonnes at present.

 Simultaneously, the Aditya Birla group company is also setting up a fully integrated greenfield aluminium complex, Aditya Aluminium, in Orissa with an alumina capacity of 1 million tonnes (expandable to 1.5 million tonnes) and aluminium capacity of 2.60 lakh tonnes. Hindalco is further investing in Utkal Alumina International Ltd, a 55:45 joint venture company with Alcan Inc. 

 This plant in Orissa will have an alumina capacity of 1-1.5 million tonnes.

 According to Hindalco, it has tied up with financial institutions and banks for debt financing to the extent of Rs 7,050 crore for the expansion plan.

 Kumar Mangalam Birla, chairman, Hindalco Industries Ltd, said, Hindalco is at the threshold of its next phase of growth and the planned expansions would transform the company into a metal producer on a global scale. The promoters are fully committed to the success of the offering.

 D. Bhattacharya, managing director of the company, said, We have structured issue keeping in view the phased funding requirements of the company and to provide investors with an option to pay in a phased manner while continuing to participate in the growth of the company.




